 so that there is little likelihood of their being ejected from the host galaxy; (iv) black holes can grow even from stellar masses to $\sim$5 × 109Msolar at high redshift z $\sim$ 6; and (v) jets produced in successive accretion episodes can have similar directions, but after several episodes the jet direction deviates significantly. Rare examples of massive holes with larger spin parameters could result from prograde coalescences with SMBHs of similar mass, and are most likely to be found in giant ellipticals. We compare these results with observation.},
author = {King, A. R. and Pringle, J. E. and Hofmann, J. A.},
doi = {10.1111/j.1365-2966.2008.12943.x},
issn = {0035-8711},
